  "chunk_index": 37,
  "summary": "Simonetta, a medium, expresses profound fear and exhaustion to Raul (also referred to as Laurie or Luca) while resting on a couch. She describes a persistent dread that something terrible will happen to her and recounts the terrifying \"darkness of nothingness\" she encounters during her work. Raul attempts to comfort her, suggesting her distress stems from the pressures of her profession and that she requires rest. He presents her with letters from Professor Loche and Dr. Gurney requesting her services, but Simonetta insists she will never summon spirits again due to a sense of great danger. Raul promises her she will not have to work again, though he notes that her contributions have been a noble service to science.\n\nSimonetta expresses particular dread regarding an upcoming séance with Madame Ix, a tall, dark, and intimidating woman with large, man-like hands who has lost her only child. Raul reproaches Simonetta for her lack of sympathy toward the grieving mother, defending the success of previous séances, such as the one involving the spirit of \"Little Emily.\" Simonetta remains anxious, fearing her work is a \"deal with the devil\" and noting her physical exhaustion. Her nervousness causes her to break a porcelain bottle while waiting for Madame Ix. Despite Simonetta's desire to cancel the appointment, Raul reminds her of the importance of the séance, emphasizing that the client is a mother seeking to see her child one last time.",
